The main research goals of this project were to develop and refine coral geochemical measurements as proxies for climate parameters, and to reconstruct past climate changes in the Red Sea region over the past several centuries.  We developed quantitative calibrations of strontium-to-calcium (Sr/Ca) ratios versus sea surface temperature (SST) for six individual coral colonies across a large SST gradient in the Red Sea.  No significant differences were found between regressions for individual colonies at full seasonal resolution, and data for all six corals were combined into a single regression to provide a calibration equation applicable to the entire region.  We also found strong and significant regressions for both winter and summer averaged data, demonstrating the potential for quantitative reconstructing past SST as a function of season.  Together, these results demonstrate the power of coral Sr/Ca as an SST proxy across a range of temporal and spatial scales, and thus the potential to reconstruct spatial SST patterns back through time.  We have reconstructed SST over the past ~230 years from two locations in the northern and central Red Sea, showing pronounced decadal-centennial scale variability in the full seasonal cycle as well as winter and summer seasons separately.  Winter season SST shows a strong correlation to the North Atlantic Oscillation (NAO) at multidecadal time scales, and combining these records with other centuries-long NAO reconstructions reveals changes in geographic stationarity of the NAO signal back through time. Winter-season SSTs in the northern and central Red Sea also show a striking pattern of antiphase decadal-centennial scale changes over the entire 230-year record.  The SST gradient appears to undergo a cycle of collapse, followed by abrupt strengthening and subsequent gradual weakening before another collapse.  Climate data and models indicate that the Red Sea SST gradient is driven by meridional wind intensity, and our records represent a new discovery of changes in wind intensity potentially occurring on a ~170-year cycle. In addition, we have developed coral barium-to-calcium (Ba/Ca) ratios as a novel proxy for eolian dust deposition.  Two corals from the central and southern Red Sea show nearly identical records of Ba/Ca in seawater, reflecting changes in Summer Asian Monsoon wind intensity over the past ~230 years.  The coral monsoon records show periodic variability at interannual to multidecadal frequencies that is strongly anticorrelated with Northern Hemisphere mean temperature.  This suggests that monsoon variability (though not intensity) should continue to decline in the face of continued anthropogenic warming in the future.  

